00:01:36.140 --> 00:01:40.869
the same time and talk about it together.

00:01:40.869 --> 00:01:42.290
Let me know what you come up with.

00:01:42.290 --> 00:01:45.579
But, as I say, he is happy to do it.

00:01:45.579 --> 00:01:48.500
Second thing.

00:01:48.500 --> 00:01:54.470
There was an interview printed in US Today,
which I have posted on the class website with

00:01:54.470 --> 00:01:57.290
Mike Griffin, the administrator.

00:01:57.290 --> 00:02:01.520
And it says NASA administrator says space
shuttle was a mistake.

00:02:01.520 --> 00:02:06.780
And so the question was what do we intend
to do about that in this class?

00:02:06.780 --> 00:02:14.100
Well, let me actually read the specific words
that Griffin uses because I think that's important.

00:02:14.100 --> 00:02:19.519
Griffin said my opinion is that the Shuttle
was a design which was extremely aggressive

00:02:19.519 --> 00:02:22.870
and just barely possible.

00:02:22.870 --> 00:02:28.580
And that's actually, I think, a slightly different
way of looking at this.

00:02:28.580 --> 00:02:35.620
I mean I would also say that Apollo was a
project that was extremely aggressive and

00:02:35.620 --> 00:02:37.550
just barely possible.

00:02:37.550 --> 00:02:42.340
And I think that it is actually NASA's business
to do things which are aggressive and just

00:02:42.340 --> 00:02:43.430
barely possible.

00:02:43.430 --> 00:02:50.930
Now, whether it was the right decision for
the country to abandon the Exploration Program

00:02:50.930 --> 00:02:58.630
after Apollo and do the Shuttle and then later
on the Space Station that's more, I think,

00:02:58.630 --> 00:02:59.780
in the political realm.

00:02:59.780 --> 00:03:07.830
And, as I think you've heard both from Dale
Myers and John Logsdon, that, in fact, there

00:03:07.830 --> 00:03:13.959
were political determining factors which didn't
really give NASA a lot of choice.

00:03:13.959 --> 00:03:22.400
Just to remind you, the basic point of this
course is not the political and economic history

00:03:22.400 --> 00:03:23.400
of the shuttle.

00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:28.980
It's a technical exploration of how we did
the shuttle.

00:03:28.980 --> 00:03:34.670
I think we would all agree that the concept
of the Shuttle was extremely aggressive and

00:03:34.670 --> 00:03:38.849
the technology was being stretched and it
was just barely possible.

00:03:38.849 --> 00:03:40.409
And, yet, we did it.

00:03:40.409 --> 00:03:47.159
And the idea of this course is to understand
how we did it and how the systems work.

00:03:47.159 --> 00:03:52.909
I think it will be interesting, when we get
towards the end of the course, maybe we'll

00:03:52.909 --> 00:03:58.720
sit down and relax and instead of having,
I think there are two kinds of open sessions

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:01.849
towards the end that I've been thinking about
what we want to do there.

00:04:01.849 --> 00:04:07.810
And in one of them I think we may just talk
a little bit and reflect on what we've learned,

00:04:07.810 --> 00:04:14.270
and that will give us an opportunity to discuss
issues like this.

00:04:14.270 --> 00:04:15.340
That's all I'm going to say about this.

00:04:15.340 --> 00:04:21.580
I don't propose that we discuss this further
today because we really are fortunate to have

00:04:21.580 --> 00:04:22.690
Bass Redd.

00:04:22.690 --> 00:04:25.470
And Aaron Cohen is going to introduce him
formally.

00:04:25.470 --> 00:04:32.500
I will just say that when I was at Johnston
Space Center last spring and I met one of

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:37.720
the older managers there and I was telling
him about our plans for this course and how

00:04:37.720 --> 00:04:43.009
Aaron was going to be a visiting professor
here and we were inviting some of the experts

00:04:43.009 --> 00:04:47.010
in the early design of the Shuttle, he said,
well, there is one guy you absolutely have

00:04:47.010 --> 00:04:48.550
to get, and that's Bass Redd.

00:04:48.550 --> 00:04:49.550
Well, we've got him.

00:04:49.550 --> 00:04:50.550
We're very fortunate.

00:04:50.550 --> 00:04:55.660
And, Aaron, I will turn it over to you and
let you explain a little bit more why we're

00:04:55.660 --> 00:04:57.990
so fortunate.

00:04:57.990 --> 00:05:07.820
Well, first I have to tell you how I found
Bass.

00:05:07.820 --> 00:05:09.330
I had a hard time finding Bass.

00:05:09.330 --> 00:05:13.419
He lives in a placed called Smithville, Texas.

00:05:13.419 --> 00:05:19.139
And, when people ask him where Smithville,
Texas is, he said it's about a few minutes

00:05:19.139 --> 00:05:20.800
after you pass resume speed.

00:05:20.800 --> 00:05:23.240
So, it's not a very well known place.

00:05:23.240 --> 00:05:25.220
But I finally found Bass.

00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:28.990
And he is truly an outstanding aerodynamicist.

00:05:28.990 --> 00:05:36.210
And the thing that is so important is that
aerodynamics, to me, from my vantage point,

00:05:36.210 --> 00:05:42.210
is really the linchpin, you might say, of
putting a system together.

00:05:42.210 --> 00:05:44.229
Aerodynamics makes the system come alive.

00:05:44.229 --> 00:05:50.850
And as you could hear from the various speakers,
from Tom Moser, and we talked a little bit

00:05:50.850 --> 00:05:54.680
about the guidance, navigation and control,
it's important for the structures.

00:05:54.680 --> 00:05:58.740
Aerodynamics is important for the structures,
it's important for the flight control system,

00:05:58.740 --> 00:06:02.330
it's important for the hydraulic system and
it's important for the heating system.

00:06:02.330 --> 00:06:09.710
So, you have to understand the aerodynamics
before you can make the vehicle actually come

00:06:09.710 --> 00:06:11.139
alive.

00:06:11.139 --> 00:06:12.860
And Bass Redd is the man to do it.

00:06:12.860 --> 00:06:17.069
He is absolutely one of the great aerodynamicists
of our times.

00:06:17.069 --> 00:06:23.110
And he started out before there was computational
fluid dynamics and the old wind tunnel testing.

00:06:23.110 --> 00:06:26.930
And now there is computational fluid dynamics,
so you're going to be in for a real treat

00:06:26.930 --> 00:06:31.889
today to hear how Bass Redd put both the Apollo
together, he did the Apollo aerodynamics,

00:06:31.889 --> 00:06:34.319
and he also did the Shuttle aerodynamics.

00:06:34.319 --> 00:06:38.729
And he is also now consulting to help NASA
do their future work.

00:06:38.729 --> 00:06:41.150
Let me now turn it over to Bass.

00:06:41.150 --> 00:06:44.389
Thank you, Aaron.

00:06:44.389 --> 00:06:48.630
It's a great honor to be with you this morning.

00:06:48.630 --> 00:06:56.500
And you sure do look young.

00:06:56.500 --> 00:07:52.890
[LAUGHTER] We will try to cover basically
-- [STATIC OBSCURES] And with that overview

00:07:52.890 --> 00:08:03.080
then of the Orbiter is how the program requirements
drove the aerodynamic configuration, probably

00:08:03.080 --> 00:08:07.510
the biggest thing in what the aerodynamic
characteristics are driven by the program

00:08:07.510 --> 00:08:08.510
requirements.

00:08:08.510 --> 00:08:12.080
And that will make a little more sense after
we get into the briefing.

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:19.199
Then the aerodynamic considerations, those
that aren't due to program requirements but

00:08:19.199 --> 00:08:23.590
just due to the basic fundamentals of aerodynamics
and the configuration that is being evaluated.

00:08:23.590 --> 00:08:27.840
We will do that for both the Orbiter and the
Integrated Vehicle.

00:08:27.840 --> 00:08:34.520
Then I'll try to tell you how the aerodynamic
design was accomplished through each of those

00:08:34.520 --> 00:08:39.870
phases, a lot of ways to work problems.

00:08:39.870 --> 00:08:46.030
Early on having powerful tools or sometimes
a curse to you because you can produce more

00:08:46.030 --> 00:08:49.420
data than the system can consume.

00:08:49.420 --> 00:08:57.670
And I remember when we first got started on
the Shuttle design, the people from structures

00:08:57.670 --> 00:09:04.000
had just finished the NASTRAN on the Apollo
and they immediately wanted enough data to

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.280
put into the NASTRAN for every configuration
that was being conceived.

00:09:08.280 --> 00:09:12.750
That's not really a smart thing to do when
you have literally hundreds of configurations

00:09:12.750 --> 00:09:13.750
to be considered.

00:09:13.750 --> 00:09:21.160
We will try to talk to you about phases, phase
A, B and C, and defining the problem areas.

00:09:21.160 --> 00:09:26.649
And then defining the aerodynamic characteristics
and do just a quick summary of the wind tunnel

00:09:26.649 --> 00:09:27.890
test program.

00:09:27.890 --> 00:09:32.300
And with some comments on how CFD might have
driven that were it available.

00:09:32.300 --> 00:09:36.300
Through the `60s and `80s these design studies
were accomplished in phases.

00:09:36.300 --> 00:09:40.959
Phase A is primarily in-house civil service
design.

00:09:40.959 --> 00:09:47.269
I don't know how well you understand the NASA
part, what the contractor part, what the civil

00:09:47.269 --> 00:09:52.920
service part is, but phase A is primarily
in-house civil service.

00:09:52.920 --> 00:10:00.920
Whenever the contractors began to feel that
this might be a real program, they began to

00:10:00.920 --> 00:10:06.990
do their in-house studies and they began to
visit and give us recommendations and ideas

00:10:06.990 --> 00:10:09.149
on their own to drive that.

00:10:09.149 --> 00:10:10.470
None of that is paid for.

00:10:10.470 --> 00:10:13.370
That's a gratuitous kind of a thing.

00:10:13.370 --> 00:10:19.930
And contractors have a bit of change set aside
to do those kinds of studies, but it's a freebee

00:10:19.930 --> 00:10:24.730
and really a super way to do things.

00:10:24.730 --> 00:10:26.970
And that's still going on today.

00:10:26.970 --> 00:10:33.120
Phase B is then you give contracts for generic
studies.

00:10:33.120 --> 00:10:40.240
Scopes out the concept feasibilities and the
program requirements and does those trades,

00:10:40.240 --> 00:10:44.010
does projected cost and timelines.

00:10:44.010 --> 00:10:52.290
By the way, before I forget it, Humboldt Mandell
on costing would be excellent.

00:10:52.290 --> 00:10:58.540
We worked quite close hand-in-hand on trying
to get those requirements and cost run together

00:10:58.540 --> 00:11:00.120
along with the weight.

00:11:00.120 --> 00:11:06.329
NASA then, after they get through this phase
B, they produce a detailed statement of work

00:11:06.329 --> 00:11:15.030
that 
is required for the phase C and D.

00:11:15.030 --> 00:11:20.339
And then phase C and D is the design and development.

00:11:20.339 --> 00:11:22.920
The Air Force separated those two.

00:11:22.920 --> 00:11:24.610
NASA always sort of put those together.

00:11:24.610 --> 00:11:27.380
So the design, development and construction.

00:11:27.380 --> 00:11:30.110
And the contractors do the detail work.

00:11:30.110 --> 00:11:33.130
NASA manages and checks it.

00:11:33.130 --> 00:11:37.850
Usually the way we operate, at least in our
area, the aerodynamic area, we had a crack

00:11:37.850 --> 00:11:44.019
team that would go back in and define the
problem, a potential solution to that problem

00:11:44.019 --> 00:11:50.400
and then suggest to the contractor they might
look at this way or that way.

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:52.650
But they really put the muscle to it.

00:11:52.650 --> 00:11:54.690
They put the final studies.

00:11:54.690 --> 00:11:58.730
They have the design documentation.

00:11:58.730 --> 00:12:06.040
And we try to steer that train as those things
happen.

00:12:06.040 --> 00:12:13.470
In the Shuttle now, phase A, we started in
1969, just shortly after the Lunar landing,

00:12:13.470 --> 00:12:14.490
they put together a small team.

00:12:14.490 --> 00:12:16.670
And this is at Johnson Space Craft Center.

00:12:16.670 --> 00:12:20.910
And that's through my knothole and the way
that I look at things.

00:12:20.910 --> 00:12:24.860
But we did end up being the lead center in
the shuttle.

00:12:24.860 --> 00:12:30.480
But we started with a small E&amp;D group that
was headed by a fellow by the name of Jim

00:12:30.480 --> 00:12:31.480
Chamberlain.

00:12:31.480 --> 00:12:35.140
Jim Chamberlain was the one that was responsible
for the Gemini Space Craft, a very unique

00:12:35.140 --> 00:12:43.120
individual gone to heaven to be with the Lord
now, reviewed by Max Faget who was head of

00:12:43.120 --> 00:12:50.080
E&amp;D and Bob Gilruth who was center director,
but that was a real privilege to work with

00:12:50.080 --> 00:12:51.080
him.

00:12:51.080 --> 00:12:55.580
What came out of that initial phase A study
is what the vehicle should be, is a small

00:12:55.580 --> 00:13:03.310
personnel vehicle with a four man crew, 10k
payload landing on the runway with about 200

00:13:03.310 --> 00:13:06.850
nautical miles cross-range.

00:13:06.850 --> 00:13:10.581
Quite different from the shuttle that we have
today, but that was during the phase A.

00:13:10.581 --> 00:13:14.780
Strong design modules in this time were developed.

00:13:14.780 --> 00:13:22.450
And, showing how the other program requirements
go with the design, the size and the program

00:13:22.450 --> 00:13:30.740
cost, there were individuals who had in their
databank, which consisted of books that they

00:13:30.740 --> 00:13:39.019
kept on their tables, were all of the aircraft,
all of the spacecraft, all of the missiles,

00:13:39.019 --> 00:13:47.709
what the weight of every individual subsystem
was based upon plots with ECLS's on how much

00:13:47.709 --> 00:13:53.440
heat they took out, on the avionics as to
how many computations they made.

00:13:53.440 --> 00:14:00.370
Well, not to chase that rabbit too far, but
basically they were down to the subsystem

00:14:00.370 --> 00:14:02.080
kind of level.

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:06.770
And then with the primary structure, secondary
structure, how that was affected by landed

00:14:06.770 --> 00:14:10.000
weights or entry weights, the thermal protection
system.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:15.420
And it was amazing what a good job that kind
of approach would do.

00:14:15.420 --> 00:14:21.550
And then we had point designs that were being
looked at both in-house at Johnson Space Craft

00:14:21.550 --> 00:14:24.860
Center, at Marshall and by all the contractors.

00:14:24.860 --> 00:14:26.980
And then all that data was fed into the system.

00:14:26.980 --> 00:14:28.580
So, that was a designed database.

00:14:28.580 --> 00:14:33.709
Some of those have been automated now and
pretty good.

00:14:33.709 --> 00:14:37.579
And they don't give you the right answers,
but the answers they give you aren't very

00:14:37.579 --> 00:14:38.870
far wrong either.

00:14:38.870 --> 00:14:44.029
They get into the ballpark for you.

00:14:44.029 --> 00:14:48.350
Phase B started in 1971.

00:14:48.350 --> 00:14:49.980
Something happened.

00:14:49.980 --> 00:14:53.389
The requirements were not dictated by NASA.

00:14:53.389 --> 00:14:57.270
The requirements were dictated by the Air
Force, at least the driving requirements.

00:14:57.270 --> 00:15:00.990
If we had our own, a small vehicle it would
have satisfied that.

00:15:00.990 --> 00:15:10.850
The Air Force requirements were 55,000 pound
payload, 60 foot long payload bay, 15 foot

00:15:10.850 --> 00:15:15.910
in diameter, it had to be returned with a
1200 nautical mile cross-range.

00:15:15.910 --> 00:15:20.430
At least 32,000 pounds of it had to be returned.

00:15:20.430 --> 00:15:22.019
It was classified at that time.

00:15:22.019 --> 00:15:23.860
It is no longer classified.

00:15:23.860 --> 00:15:28.790
You can use your imagination to figure out
what kind of payload that you would want to

00:15:28.790 --> 00:15:33.360
go up into a high inclination orbit and bring
back in one pass.

00:15:33.360 --> 00:15:37.050
Where that would take you and why you'd have
to get back that quickly.

00:15:37.050 --> 00:15:42.639
But those were the requirements that were
fed into phase B.

00:15:42.639 --> 00:15:46.000
Maximum reusability did not come from the
Air Force.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.050
That came from the NASA side as that was part
of technology.

00:15:49.050 --> 00:15:51.570
NASA has two basic jobs to do.

00:15:51.570 --> 00:15:58.199
One is the design of the vehicle, the delivering
of the hardware, accomplishing the mission,

00:15:58.199 --> 00:16:04.740
but the other requirement for NASA is that
it increased the technology.

00:16:04.740 --> 00:16:08.829
Going where no man has gone before, yes, but
doing things that man has not done before

00:16:08.829 --> 00:16:11.350
in a better, faster way.

00:16:11.350 --> 00:16:18.610
And so maximum reusability was a goal that
the engineers were handed.

00:16:18.610 --> 00:16:19.860
Soft ride.

00:16:19.860 --> 00:16:24.730
They wanted to be able to a congressman or
a senator up in it.

00:16:24.730 --> 00:16:28.070
[LAUGHTER] A neat thing.

00:16:28.070 --> 00:16:31.029
Multi-center participation.

00:16:31.029 --> 00:16:34.260
If you ever get Hum up here, that cost you.

00:16:34.260 --> 00:16:41.990
Any time you break a job down and give it
to more than one center or more than one contractor,

00:16:41.990 --> 00:16:45.731
it's like Humpty-Dumpty, you break him apart,
you've got to put him back together again.

00:16:45.731 --> 00:16:51.530
And it takes a lot of eyes and elbows on both
sides to accomplish that.

00:16:51.530 --> 00:16:56.389
And basically, once you break something down,
you've increased your cost by 30% to 40% to

00:16:56.389 --> 00:16:58.420
put it back together again.

00:16:58.420 --> 00:17:08.850
Now, NASA has to have, under congressional
mandate, contracts in every state in the union.

00:17:08.850 --> 00:17:16.439
Multi-center participation drives a great
number of things so I felt it needed to be

00:17:16.439 --> 00:17:19.270
on the chart.

00:17:19.270 --> 00:17:26.720
But the big thing that you need to know as
engineers, sometimes you cannot set your own

00:17:26.720 --> 00:17:27.720
program requirements.

00:17:27.720 --> 00:17:31.360
They are dictated to you for strange reasons.

00:17:31.360 --> 00:17:38.120
And you have to play the hand that you're
dealt.

00:17:38.120 --> 00:17:43.270
Phase C and D, we had four contractors that
bid on phase C and D.

00:17:43.270 --> 00:17:46.870
The interesting thing is Rockwell was the
only contractor that bid within the allocated

00:17:46.870 --> 00:17:48.070
funds.

00:17:48.070 --> 00:17:52.720
They also had the best proposal, but that
was very interesting.

00:17:52.720 --> 00:17:59.419
What they did was use the aerodynamic database
that was developed in phase A and in phase

00:17:59.419 --> 00:18:01.820
B for their design analysis.

00:18:01.820 --> 00:18:05.789
They augmented that, they did some in-house
testing, and Rockwell said we can do it for

00:18:05.789 --> 00:18:11.450
that amount of money but only if you don't
change anything, NASA.

00:18:11.450 --> 00:18:15.520
And we changed things.

00:18:15.520 --> 00:18:19.460
They had a smaller orbiter, and we rejected
that very early on.

00:18:19.460 --> 00:18:21.880
It had no capability for weight growth.

00:18:21.880 --> 00:18:27.810
And we showed that every program that has
ever existed grew in weight by at least 5%,

00:18:27.810 --> 00:18:29.179
10%, 15%.

00:18:29.179 --> 00:18:34.309
And so the Orbiter was sized up just a little
bit larger than the one that they had proposed

00:18:34.309 --> 00:18:36.580
with their agreement.

00:18:36.580 --> 00:18:40.640
Aaron probably had a contract change authorization
because of that.

00:18:40.640 --> 00:18:43.280
But, anyway, we did that right at the beginning.

00:18:43.280 --> 00:18:53.270
What we did also aerodynamically during that
phase B is we developed a complete database

00:18:53.270 --> 00:18:58.740
in the nation's best facility to be used for
what we call verification analysis.

00:18:58.740 --> 00:19:09.200
And that database is very well documented,
and we will talk about that a little bit more.

00:19:09.200 --> 00:19:10.200
Program requirements.

00:19:10.200 --> 00:19:16.400
May I ask, before you go onto program requirements,
could you say something about kind of, you

00:19:16.400 --> 00:19:18.970
talked about the aerodynamic database, but
