00:25:35.080 --> 00:25:42.000
But the cost constraints, there was a great
move afoot to have a return to the launch

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:47.460
site booster, manned booster, if you please,
but the cost and constraints and the size

00:25:47.460 --> 00:25:51.890
of the vehicle got pretty big.

00:25:51.890 --> 00:26:01.260
The wing vehicle loads were significantly
reduced by the parallel burn.

00:26:01.260 --> 00:26:09.120
You've got the orbiter tucked in between the
solid rocket boosters and the external tank

00:26:09.120 --> 00:26:11.840
versus an orbiter that would be on the end.

00:26:11.840 --> 00:26:18.110
It makes a great difference in the structural
loads that the aerodynamics produces.

00:26:18.110 --> 00:26:23.940
Solid rocket booster mismatch decreased or
dictated an increased beta dispersion.

00:26:23.940 --> 00:26:30.270
Typically on an end-to-end vehicle you've
got everything kind of tucked in pretty tightly.

00:26:30.270 --> 00:26:34.660
On this one the SRBs are spread, any mismatch
at burnout and we had some big beta dispersions

00:26:34.660 --> 00:26:37.700
that still haunt us a little bit today.

00:26:37.700 --> 00:26:39.080
Soft ride requirement.

